{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":302031,"duration_api_ms":298207,"num_turns":28,"result":"","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"c2e4cf43-b6ee-4cdb-b573-8eeec5621178","total_cost_usd":1.39503705,"usage":{"input_tokens":24,"cache_creation_input_tokens":66375,"cache_read_input_tokens":1178038,"output_tokens":9656,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":66375,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-opus-4-6":{"inputTokens":24,"outputTokens":9656,"cacheReadInputTokens":1178038,"cacheCreationInputTokens":66375,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":1.2453827499999999,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":64000},"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001":{"inputTokens":84,"outputTokens":9393,"cacheReadInputTokens":548353,"cacheCreationInputTokens":38216,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.14965430000000002,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":32000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"amendments":[{"body":"The `json_fill_none` function (fs.rs:2284-2300) silently converts serialization/deserialization errors into `None`, which is indistinguishable from a structural merge rejection. In the `StartJournalDetails::merge` and `CompletionJournalDetails::merge` callers, this means a serde bug (e.g., a future field type that fails to round-trip through `serde_json::Value`) would appear as a rejected merge, causing duplicate journal events to be appended instead of being merged. Consider returning `Result<Option<T>, ...>` or at minimum adding a `tracing::warn` inside `json_fill_none` when `to_value` or `from_value` fails, so operators can distinguish serde failures from legitimate merge rejections.","rationale":"Silent error swallowing in a repair path can mask latent bugs. Today the types are simple (String, Option<String>, DateTime) so this won't fire, but the function is generic and future-facing — its whole purpose is to be forward-compatible with new fields. A new field with a non-trivial serde implementation could silently break journal repair without any diagnostic signal."},{"body":"`#[serde(deny_unknown_fields)]` on `StartJournalDetails` and `CompletionJournalDetails` (model.rs:357, 383) prevents parsing journal entries that contain fields added by a newer code version. If the binary is rolled back after new-format entries are written, `parse()` returns `None`, journal merge is skipped, and duplicate events accumulate. This is data-safe but operationally surprising. Add a comment documenting this forward-compatibility tradeoff next to the `deny_unknown_fields` attribute, or switch to a lenient parse for existing journal entries (only use `deny_unknown_fields` in the round-trip test assertions where it actually catches drift).","rationale":"The struct consolidation was done specifically to prevent drift, and `deny_unknown_fields` is one of the tools used. But there's a tension: `deny_unknown_fields` prevents drift on parse but also prevents forward compatibility on rollback. Since the round-trip tests already catch drift at compile time (the primary goal), `deny_unknown_fields` at runtime is belt-and-suspenders with a downside. At minimum, the tradeoff should be documented so a future developer doesn't spend time debugging why journal repair stopped working after a rollback."}],"summary":"The implementation correctly addresses all three issues from the project spec. Issue 1 (struct drift): eliminated by consolidating to a single canonical struct in model.rs with round-trip tests. Issue 2 (runless-to-named completion): correctly implemented with started_at-gated matching and comprehensive guard arms. Issue 3 (plan_hash auto-population): correctly auto-populates from snapshot only on new entry creation, intentionally avoiding existing-row backfill to prevent mislabeling after plan evolution. All 353 tests pass, 13 new tests provide thorough coverage of the happy paths and key edge cases (plan evolution replays, started_at mismatches, legacy row preservation). The code is clean with well-placed comments explaining the invariants. Two minor amendments proposed: (1) json_fill_none silently swallows serde errors, and (2) deny_unknown_fields has a forward-compatibility tradeoff on rollback that should be documented."},"fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"629f265c-71b6-4507-b229-bd989f3906cd"}
